A workaround is the following:

public void revealNode() {
    getTree().showItem(getTree().getItem(CHILDREN - 1));
}

Given that reveal() takes an element or tree path and thus does not have information about indices, all we can do is to fix reveal() so that it materializes tree nodes until it finds the one to reveal.  As you point out, this defeats the purpose of using VIRTUAL.  To properly fix this, we would need to add API, or document that in order to reveal an item, you should use Tree.showItem().

